Mark Edward Stahl (mes@queens.ece.cmu.edu) wrote:
: As was pointed out in another thread on a.s.pgp, by signing your own
: key, you verify that you hold the corresponding secret key.  Also, in
: PGP, the signature on the key includes the ID string. Hence, no one
: can edit the key's ID without making all presently attached signature
: invalid.  A public key signed with its own secret key is
: "self-checking" in the sense that, whoever gave the key its ID *must*
: hold the corresponding secret key.

: Just be sure to verify (by fingerprints or whatever) that the key
: belongs to the name on the ID.

: The moral: Sign your own key.

Wouldn't the moral really be: "Don't accept a key that hasn't been
signed by its owner"?

Ron Wilson
